Turret?
"...Excuse me?" She shifts her attention to the new arrival with a skeptical expression.

This is a young girl, probably about 10 or so.

"I've seen all the other people before, but I haven't seen you. You look different."
She taps her chin in thought for only a couple seconds. "Oh. Eulogia."
She smiles. "That's me!"
She stares for a little bit, visibly unsure of what to do, and checks around to see if there's any sort of call bell in her turret.
There is the torch you are supposed to light specifically when people are attacking, but that's the only clearly visible signal.
She mutters "shit" under her breath. "...I'll preface this by saying that I respect the crown very much, and this extends to you too. This is my post. I work here now. Please leave."
She blows a raspberry. "You're no fun. Merl was..." She faints.
"Joliene, you--Oh, there she is." Solnit also arrives from below. He slings her over his shoulder a little less than delicately. "Have you spoken to anyone today?"

Giving little but a sympathetic frown and half-surprised "yeah" to the child's predicament before Solnit arrived, Joliene lays her forearms by her lap. "...I haven't, aside from the child here. Was I supposed to? I figured I would be more useful stationing myself immediately."

"I suppose I can't blame you for settling into routine. Probably admirable for the militant. And I can hardly imagine *she's* told you anything relevant."

He sighs, and turns around with a flourish, robe blowing in the wind. 
"There's been an incident *within* the palace grounds. Normally, this shouldn't have anything to do with you, but I guess it does somehow? You were requested, at any rate. And they seem to have deigned me the one to handle communication with you. Please, follow me."
Her eyes widen, a little shocked, but it takes no time at all to settle and convert into resigned annoyance. Another problem to add to the pile, presumably. "...Right." She follows.

Along the way, the two run into the queen, scribbling notes onto a pocketbook. Solnit coughs and holds out the child.

"Oh, thank goodness. Did she bother you?" She asks Joliene.
"...I didn't know you allowed your child to wander through the palace like this. She seems... sickly. More than I was anticipating."
"Well, not like it concerns me. I was called?"

She sighs. "I don't. She's not supposed to leave her room without telling me, let alone... Ah, yes, I think that was Dextrum's doing? Right over in his study." She points in a direction.

((I failed to mention this when she showed up but eulogia is wearing like. what can most accurately be described as a fucking gamer headset. this is important to specify))

((TAP but awesome))

"...I see. Thank you. I'll go see him now." She does exactly that yeah.
Eastern Advisor Virtos Dextrum, a quirky portly fellow, is sitting in front of his desk when you walk in. "Ah, Joliene, good. We're in a spot of trouble and I believe you can help."
In front? She blinks briefly. "Excuse me, we're?"
"Solnit and I, I suppose, but a whole lot of people are, even if they don't know it. Come over into this back room." He heads into a room further back into this office.
She quirks a brow, and reluctantly wheels forward.

After entering the door, Joliene finds herself in a cosmic space void looking place. There's clearly a floor that she's wheeling on, but there's not a visible ground. ((It looks kinda like the stanley parable zen room I guess)). In the center(?????) of this space is a point of light, and adjacent to that is what looks like a floating crystal.

"You get it now?" Solnit.
"I don't see why she would." Dextrum. "This is a magically constructed space. There's a real room, but it's been altered."

Joliene's surprise is perhaps not as intense as you'd expect, though she's still drinking in the visual spectacle. That said, she indeed does not get it. "...Nothing in this 'place' registers as something I can assist with, let alone a problem."
"Are you well-read on the subject of prophecies?" Solnit asks this.
"...I may have passing knowledge on them," Joliene says, and though it's certainly possible, she absolutely no confidence that it's actually true. "But I'm not well-read by any means."

"This is a dead ringer for the 'cocoon' mentioned by Alto and Exevel. The signature of the end times,"

Dextrum interrupts him. "Whoa, whoa. I wouldn't go that far. But it's true that this is noteworthy. Joliene, in the center of this room is... a closed space. A pocket dimension, whatever one might call it. Though not the simple kind that can be entered just like a door or window. All that someone can do physically by interacting with that light is injure themselves. It's an heirloom of sorts, first developed by my grandfather, and iterated since."

He walks over to the crystal. "This, though... I didn't make. I wouldn't think you have any clue about what in blazes is going on with this."
She pauses. "...No. No I don't. So it just showed up here one day, and you're concerned because it's a bad omen?"

"I'm concerned because it's *anything*. Solnit -- wizard-secretary-watchman-lawyer-messenger-professor renaissance man that he is -- thinks it matches up with a description of some phenomenon in reputable ancient texts, and also with a description of the apocalypse in substantially less reputable texts. And I do care about the former!" Solnit grumbles obscenities. Dextrum continues. "Mostly, it's highly unusual for what I assume is happening to occur -- that the space is exerting influence outside itself."
((I have spent way too much time lately having a character just say shit at PCs))

"...huh." Once more, she pauses, scratching her nape with a glare of indifference. "I sincerely don't understand how I'm supposed to help with... whatever's going on here. I hope you realize you've dragged me away from my post. I do better with observable reality than vague phenomenon alluding to a story that may or may not have been accurately recounted through generations."

“I also agree.” Solnit.

“Well, erm, it’s because I have a vague hunch. You were checked for both weapons and any sort of curses when you first came here… and something about you matches this place.”

"Was I?" She thinks this, and stops herself before she can say it out loud.

"Hmn. I don't see the resemblance."

She puts a hand to her temple and lets loose a gradually-building look of utter bewilderment. "Okay. That's not a real name. I still don't know what's happening or how it involves me in any way."

"...If either of the two options, I'd lean towards the latter." She does not need to gesture to the wheelchair for what she's referring to to be obvious. She sighs. "Please excuse me." She attempts to leave the room.
She is able to leave the room, as two of the three people in the room support this course of action and the third is at a loss.
Before returning to her post, she attempts to find Zita. Her first guess is Eulogia's room, but if she isn't there, she still continues looking.

Joliene can find Zita, fiddling with some kind of string. “Ah, hello, Mrs. Swansong. I don’t know what the advisor wanted with you, but we’ve already arranged to cover for your absence, not knowing how long it would take. If you’re done with him, I guess you’ve got the rest of the day off.” She doesn’t look up saying this.

She opens her mouth to say something, but a breath hitches in her throat. "What?! ...Sorry, excuse me, I... what? Huh? You can't-..." Joliene didn't finish the thought. She very much can. It was a fair decision and she couldn't bring herself to not respect it, annoying as it was.

"...Ahem. I wasn't here to ask about that, actually. Did anybody let a... 'Arrive Sinestre' into the palace? That's a name, by the way."
“Hm? Yes, she…” She stops and rolls her eyes. “*They* would be the Western Advisor. Rather antisocial, but good enough at the job. Any reason?”

"They?" She blinks. "She was acting unprofessionally, that's all, but by the sounds of it, that shouldn't be surprising. Doesn't care for Dextrum, apparently. You might want to send someone to solve that dispute."
"I can't picture what she would advise."

“Oh, lord. Those two have been at it for as long as I known them, and that’s quite some time. It’s best to stay away while they sort whatever is going on out. They really are both fully capable on matters that don’t directly involve the other.”

"I was planning on it. Thank you." She leaves the queen to continue doing whatever it is she hopes to accomplish with the string.

She may have been dismissed for the day, but there was still work to be done, though the work is woefully uninteresting. She'd need some sort of representation for the trial, after all, and she wasn't planning on representing herself.

Can the phone number she got from Elon be entered in her PDA anywhere?

Joliene is approached by the receptionist. “Oh, there you are. Im terribly sorry to bluster into your personal life, but there’s just no guarantee mail would be fast enough. …The trial is tomorrow, Joliene. Some nonsense moved it up.”

Joliene is about to respond to PH's most recent message when she hears her voice. "Tomorrow?! Well, that's- that would *almost* be good news! I still haven't found any representation..." She had a sour tone. "I've been busy with my job, you know. I suppose if there's any day that's good to have off, it's this one."
“Yes, there should still be some time… are you aware of any legal experts?”
She repeats the sequence of digits given to her by Elon. "...If you can't do anything with that, then no. No I'm not."

“Well, I know Dreng just showed up in the capital again. Though he’s a little shady. You could also opt for a public defender, or rely on the government in a different way. I mean, when I served in this palace, they covered my legal concerns.”

"Dreng? A... travelling lawyer? Or was he on vacation?" She pauses. "Letting the kingdom assemble a defense for me doesn't sound like a bad option either, though if they want to involve themselves in a personal dispute I'm not sure."

“Yeah, Hirer Dreng. Used to be impossible to avoid his stupid poster ads, but I guess he’s fallen off in recent years. I can’t say I ever had a divorce while working for the government, no. Probably wouldn’t hurt to check, I guess.”
"You're right about that. I'll try and check with every option I have. Consulting more opinions never hurts — Hell, I could possibly even build a team. Thanks for your help."
“I’m happy to be of assistance. You—well, I feel for you. Nobody should be stuck in a loveless arrangement.”

She nods solemnly. "I'll let you get back to your own business, now."

Since she's already in the palace, she's going back to find Zita to ask about legal representation. Seems reasonable.
She is not where Joliene saw her last.
She keeps looking, asking guards if necessary.
“I believe Her Majesty has retired to her quarters.” A Guard says this.
"That late already?" She strokes her jaw. "Do you know who I may ask about the legal benefits of working under the crown?"
He scratches his chin. “Solnit might know about that kind of thing? Or Frank, since he’s responsible for most guard hires. I would say the advisors, but they’re uh, occupied as of now.”

"...Assuming Solnit has given up trying to separate them, I'll go see him."

She tries to do so.
She can find him wandering the halls. “Oh, it’s you. What is it? I am contractually obligated to be at your service.” He laughs at his own wit.

Solnit humour

"I was hoping to ask about the sort of legal representation workers under the crown receive."

His eyes light up, and he smirks, stretching out his arms from within his robes. “You’re looking at it. I don’t lose, and those under the employ of the crown don’t have to pay.” He returns to his default posture and expression. “Of course, you’re free to have whatever representation you’re able to hire. But I am the specialist; all that the crown will provide that isn’t me is the same sort of defense any civilian would receive.”

Her eyes widen some. "Oh. Well, alright then. I trust you're knowledgeable on practically every important legal matter, then. Though, I have to ask... you're not *opposed* to a co-counsel or two, are you? I have a trial coming up tomorrow and would like a fair swathe of experts at my defense."

“Tch.” He looks to the side.
“I wouldn’t drop your case over something so petty, no. But I’ll ask that you gather whoever you’re working with by the night before the proceedings, such that I may converse with them as well as you.”
"...I'll try my hardest, but one of my representatives may show up on the day of. I apologize. The proceedings were very sudden. I'll go see if I can hire another."
“Damn. What day?”
"T... tomorrow." She does not mention that she just said so.
“Mm. How could I forget. I’ll see you later, then.” He wanders off.

It's impersonal. They'd think I only had the opportunity to hone my skill as a fighter due to an excess of free time. It's unrelatable and infeasible... so, to prove them wrong, I decided that I needed a family life."

"...I don't particularly remember how it happened. I met Bonnell *somewhere*, for sure. There may have been some sort of spark. He's a good person. Friendly. A trophy husband, for my purposes. I don't feel any sort of love for him any more, and above all else, I need some time for myself."
"...I hope that answers that."

Hirer clasps his hands together below his chin, taking in what you’ve said. He says nothing, for a time.

“I’m sorry to hear that, Joliene. Finding out that you can no longer find a way to make things work...”

He shakes his head. “There’s some confidentiality stuff I have to go through. All of what we’ve discussed thus far is within the bounds of information a lawyer can request from a prospective client. And to assure you, if I voluntarily and freely choose to turn down your case, all we’ve discussed would be completely illegal for me to mention elsewhere. Not that anything you’ve said so far makes me not want to accept.”

“I have two more questions. The first is a personal curiosity, it doesn’t really matter. The second will be the conclusion of this mock ‘interview’.”

He looks you in the eyes. “Firstly, do you have much experience in legal matters?”
"...I do not. I've never been directly involved. I suppose this won't be able to be the same."
“Alright. That’s kind of what I expected. The concluding question, for posterity, is this: what is the full legal name of the partner you are planning on separating from?”
"Bonnell Swansong. If he has a middle name, I don't know it."

Joliene has been around magic users enough to know what magic being used is like, and that’s certainly not what’s happening right now. But there still seems to be something beyond the physical in what has just shifted in the atmosphere.

“You’ve been a great help. I’d love to take your case, really. I can understand and empathize with your plight, it doesn’t seem like it’d be an infeasible time commitment, and it really does seem like I could resolve things in your benefit with my abilities. But…”

“Well, there are *factors beyond my control* preventing me from doing so. Conflict of interest rules prevent me from taking your case; your direct opposition party, a Bonnell Swansong, hired me just yesterday!” He maintains his shit eating grin.

“And as a result of the terms of our contract, I’m legally mandated to stick with my guns, stay with the guy who got to me first. Can’t leave him for you, Jo!”

He chuckles.

“So, because of rules *I am not responsible for*, my desire to work with you is prevented. I’m sure what you told me can be relevant in court, though! It’s rule one of the business, war hero: don’t trust anyone before you’ve put pen to paper. Rule two is don’t let the door hit you on your way out.”

Up?

Up as in he was reading some documents.

Joliene wheels herself aside, and attempts to not listen to every legal-related thing she can get away with. Still, that's intriguing. "Have you heard of it before?"

Thelma Receptionist speaks up. “Actually, the two of us have already m—“

“Don’t care!” Solnit drags Ogden into an adjacent room.
"He's not always this bad. Are you prepared for today?" Thelma.

She watches her attorneys leave the room, putting a thoughtful hand to her chin. Solnit truly is as knowledgeable as he claims to be if he knows about America somehow. This was worth looking into. Later, of course.

"...I'm as prepared as I can be. This doesn't require much of me, right? All this requires is my presence."

"I'd like to reassure you, but it may not be that simple. If things were only a minor conflict, that would be the case, but it would be bizarre for this to reach court at all without greater strife at play. And if this were a straightforward monetary dispute, Solnit could wipe the floor with them. But... I don't really know what's happening. I think this could become something that requires you to speak. Maybe. Dreng, Bonnell's lawyer, is also a force to be reckoned with... for unpredictability if nothing else.
